\section{Details of Experiments Setup}
\subsection{Data Evaluation Metrics Settings}
We use the OpenDataArena-Tool (footnote https://github.com/OpenDataArena/OpenDataArena-Tool) to evaluate data, and follow the default settings.
The specific data evaluation metrics settings in our experiments are as follows:
\begin{enumerate}[label={\bf {{$\bullet$}}}, leftmargin=*, topsep=0.5ex, itemsep=-0.5ex, partopsep=0.75ex, parsep=0.75ex, partopsep=0pt, wide, labelindent=0pt]
\item \textbf{IFD}. We use Qwen2.5-3B-Instruct to calculate IFD. Notably, samples with IFD > 1 are considered abnormal following~\cite{IFD}. Therefore, to precisely calculate its correlation, we replace those scores with $0$.
\item \textbf{DEITA}. We follow~\cite{Deita} and use the Complexity score $\times$ Quality score as the final data score, with scores calculated by the official checkpoints.
\item \textbf{RewardModelScore}. We use Skywork-Reward-V2-Llama-3.1-8B-30M~\cite{skywork} to calculate the reward score.
\item \textbf{VendiScore}. We use Qwen3-Embedding-0.6B to compute embeddings and employ Euclidean distance as the similarity metric in VendiScore.
\end{enumerate}
\subsection{Evaluation Setup}
\label{appx:evaluation-setup}
All downstream evaluations are conducted using OpenCompass (footnote https://github.com/open-compass/opencompass). The specific evaluation settings are as follows:
\begin{enumerate}[label={\bf {{$\bullet$}}}, leftmargin=*, topsep=0.5ex, itemsep=-0.5ex, partopsep=0.75ex, parsep=0.75ex, partopsep=0pt, wide, labelindent=0pt]
\item \textbf{PHYSICS}. We use xVerify-9B-C as an evaluator and report the average accuracy on all sub-tasks.
\item \textbf{AIME'25}. We sample 8 samples for 2025's questions, including PART I and PART II and take the average accuracy as the final score. We use xVerify-9B-C as an evaluator.
\item \textbf{LiveCodeBench}. We use the officially recommended prompt and report pass@1. We use LCBCGgenerationEvaluator as the evaluator.
\item \textbf{ClimaQA}. We use xVerify-9B-C as the evaluator and report the average accuracy on all sub-tasks.
\item \textbf{OpenFinData}. We use OpenFinDataKWEvaluator as the evaluator and report the average accuracy on all sub-tasks.
\item \textbf{CHID}. We report the average accuracy of dev and test set.
\end{enumerate}
\section{Prompt Template}
\begin{center}
\begin{tcolorbox}
\textbf{Prompt for Description Generator}:\\
\text{# Task Description}
\text{{{ task_description }}}
# Benchmark
## {{ benchmark.name }}
{{ benchmark.description }}
# Available Hugging Face Training Datasets
{% for item in datasets -%}
## {{ item.dataset_id }}
{{ item.examples }}
{% endfor -%}
---
Based on the task description, test data (Benchmark), and available Hugging Face training datasets, design a feasible **data processing plan** that includes:
(1) Selecting suitable raw data from the available Hugging Face training datasets;
(2) The data processing workflow: transforming the selected raw data into SFT training data.
The data processing plan will guide code generation and data production. Ensure it is comprehensive, practically feasible, and avoids ambiguous, vague, or meaningless statements.
A high-quality SFT dataset should possess the following characteristics: **High quality (accurate samples without noise)**, **Diversity (covering varied objectives)**, **Relevance (highly pertinent to the target vertical domain)**.
Important Notes:
- Select suitable and commonly used datasets from available HuggingFace repositories, prioritizing those with complete information, clearly defined fields, and alignment with experimental objectives. **Do not use benchmark data for training.** Do not utilize datasets, segmentation schemes, or configuration files not provided by HuggingFace.
- When designing data processing workflows, base them on the actual information within the given dataset. Do not make assumptions about the dataset's content.
- When constructing training data, inputs and outputs should form coherent question-answer dialogues. If context information related to the output exists in the data, design methods within the construction scheme to embed this context appropriately into the input. If dialogues in the benchmark feature special formats (e.g., multiple-choice questions, fill-in-the-blank, formatting constraints), ensure alignment with the benchmark's task format during data construction.
- Finalize data processing into a dialogue format directly usable for model training:
  {“dialogs”: [{“role”: “user”, “content”: “User content”}, {“role”: “assistant”, ‘content’: “Assistant content”}]}
- When planning the data processing workflow, flexibly utilize LLM inference services, including but not limited to: extracting instruction data from heterogeneous sources, employing LLM for data augmentation and synthesis, and conducting instruction evaluation or annotation on samples. Clearly specify the construction method for LLM prompts.
Generate the data processing plan in the following format; do not include other content:
## Training Data
[
    {“dataset_id”: “accurate dataset_id”, “split”: “required split”, “name”: “required configuration name”, ‘sample_num’: “required sample count”, ‘reason’: “reason for selecting this dataset”},
    ...
]
## Data Processing Workflow
[Data Processing Workflow]
\end{tcolorbox}
\end{center}

